Perfect! I found the issue. In the `pow` method around line 1492, there is a section that handles the special case when `x < 0` (negative base):

```java
/* Handle special case x<0 */
if (x < 0) {
    // y is an even integer in this case
    if (y >= TWO_POWER_52 || y <= -TWO_POWER_52) {
        return pow(-x, y);
    }

    if (y == (long) y) {
        // If y is an integer
        return ((long)y & 1) == 0 ? pow(-x, y) : -pow(-x, y);
    } else {
        return Double.NaN;
    }
}
```

The problem is with the check `y == (long) y`. When `y = 5000000000000001.0`, this should equal `(long) y = 5000000000000001L`, but due to floating-point precision issues, the comparison might fail. The value y = (5 + 1e-15) * 1e15 = 5000000000000001.0, which is representable as a long, but the comparison `y == (long) y` might fail due to precision loss.

Let me check what `TWO_POWER_52` is:

